export const batch145 = {
  'how-to-do-nothing.json': {
    base: { id: 'how-to-do-nothing', title: 'How to Do Nothing', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781661181028 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'Doing nothing can be a doorway to real learning and quiet',
        text: 'Most of the time, what feels like nothing is really your mind quietly taking in the world. One way it does this is through deep listening. Deep listening is the act of hearing the sounds of daily life, from the hum of a fan to birds outside. It pulls you gently into the present. The depth of this kind of attention shapes how much peace you feel, no matter how busy your head has been.\n\nMany people have forgotten the value of doing nothing. Yet nothing often works better than something. Across history, silence has been used as a quiet kind of power. It can irritate those who want to control you. That is why learning to be still can be a form of strength.\n\nWhen speaking up feels hard, stepping back can speak for you. Jenny Odell writes clearly about how stillness can change things, and she shows why it matters for a healthy society. If you feel too worn out to keep shouting, this book is a good place to start.'
      },
      {
        title: 'A quiet hour alone lets you look closely at where you stand',
        text: 'This stretch of life is often called the removal phase, and it is built around the art of stepping back.\n\nThere are times when doing nothing is the most useful thing you can do. Boredom, which comes from stillness, gives you room to think. A lot of people have sold off their hours. They have been told that if they are not busy, they are failing. That is not true. You do not need to be useful the moment you wake up. You need space to be still and to notice what is going on inside.\n\nDoing nothing does not mean you have to stop all action. It is more like a pause to look at the cracks. From that pause, you can return with more focus and less stress.\n\nIf you need to step back from the noise to feel calm, do not do it alone. Build or find a small group of people who support you. Cutting yourself off from everyone can leave you tired and less able to get things done.\n\nMany people think turning your back on the world is the way to peace. In fact, doing that can drain you. You do not have to leave society to find comfort in stillness.\n\nFelix Levi was a busy worker who burned out. He and his partner, Brooke Dean, went to Cambodia. They meditated there without their phones. By the end, they both felt at ease. On the flight home, Felix noticed how glued to their screens the other travelers were. He wanted to change that. So he started a Digital Detox camp. People came, put their phones away, and remembered how to be with each other. The idea worked. Many guests found new creative hobbies and time for real fun.\n\nFelix did not help people by cutting them off from the world. He helped them by swapping screen time for face time.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Doing nothing can quietly challenge how life is supposed to work',
        text: 'A lot of people feel uneasy watching someone do nothing. They think everyone should always be busy.\n\nWhen you stop and do nothing, it can make others uncomfortable. It can also show that much of what looks like productivity is just pressure in disguise.\n\nTaking time to do nothing gives you space to choose more carefully. It opens your mind to new views. You start to see angles you missed before.\n\nThis is not a call to be lazy. It is a way to give your mind room to breathe. Stillness can lead to bold action, just as it did during the 1932 longshoremen strike. Dock workers at the port were paid very little for nearly twenty hours a day of hard labor. If they complained, they were replaced. They formed a union. The bosses refused fair pay. So on May 9, 1933, the workers walked off the job. Their inaction changed the rules.\n\nWorkers around the world have used strikes for thousands of years. The tactic still works.\n\nMany people now worry about the attention economy. That is the online space where everyone is fighting to be seen. Some think the best answer is to quit these platforms. But leaving is not the same as building a better habit.\n\nA flat refusal does not give you a new life on its own. The better path is to learn how to use these tools in a moderate way, so they do not use you.'
      },
      {
        title: 'How you see things is shaped by your own attention',
        text: 'You build the picture, and you also have to read it. Something may look dull or pointless when really you have only been looking at it from one angle.\n\nA new place can feel strange at first, full of sounds you do not recognize. After a film or a trip, you start to hear those same sounds everywhere. That is curiosity at work. Curiosity pulls your attention toward the small things.\n\nAttention and curiosity let you see past the surface. They help you ask about what is hidden.\n\nHow long you look shapes what you see. How long you listen shapes what you hear. The more you pay attention to something, the more clearly it shows up.\n\nAttention is a state of being open. It assumes there is always something new. When you sit in this state, you stop acting as if you know it all.\n\nRealities can shift. If you and others agree on a new way of seeing, you can build a shared reality that changes how everyone looks at the world.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Life can look unfair until you change the angle you look from',
        text: 'It may feel like others are blocking you. Then, when you move, you may find you were the one in their way.\n\nYou have to make space for other people. Life is a bit like a busy store, full of strangers with their own plans and moods.\n\nA good life means learning to live with friends and with people who see things differently.\n\nThe people near you are more likely to help you than those far away. That is why you should build ties with the neighbors you already have.\n\nMany people trust online friends more than the people next door. That is risky. When you need help, the stranger in your building is more likely to show up than someone online.\n\nWhen people gather, they share ideas and form groups. That is how a community grows.\n\nThe online world reflects the real world. When we balance both without giving up real life, our communities grow faster.'
      },
      {
        title: 'To find context, first admit there is more to the story',
        text: 'Context comes from attention. The more you pay attention, the more of it you pick up.\n\nWhen you arrive somewhere new, you can sense if the place is friendly or cold. Animals do this very clearly. They listen. They watch. Then they decide how to respond.\n\nContext shapes the order in which you do things.\n\nThe world pours out information at us. Context helps you sort out what matters.\n\nYou need to spend time on things that add value to your life. That requires you to protect some hours for yourself.\n\nWhen you focus on what adds value, you have less time for endless scrolling. Caring for people also means caring for the place you live.\n\nYour surroundings shape what you pay attention to. In turn, what you pay attention to reflects who you are.'
      },
      {
        title: 'A few final thoughts',
        text: 'There will be a time in your life when you need to do nothing in order to do something. That time arrives when you understand the value of stillness and use it to find peace. People are shaped by the world around them, which is why context, attention, peace, and nature all matter. The more you pay attention, the more you understand life.\n\nDoing nothing does not make you useless. If your inaction is not making a mark, you are probably doing it the wrong way. Inaction can be a form of protest. When you step away from a bad system, you are standing up for people now and for those who come after.\n\nTry this. Carve out a few hours for a digital detox. Use that time to remember what real human connection feels like.'
      }
    ]
  },

  'how-to-winter-harness-your-mindset-to-thrive-on-cold-dark-or-difficult-days.json': {
    base: { id: 'how-to-winter-harness-your-mindset-to-thrive-on-cold-dark-or-difficult-days', title: 'How to Winter', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781651946082 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'Under the cover of darkness',
        text: 'Old Norse myths told of a long winter that would last three years before the end of the world. Slavic tales warned of Moroz, a cold spirit who danced with death. Inuit stories spoke of icy beasts that came from the snowfields to hunt people. For most of history, winter has been feared or disliked. Even now, many people feel a quiet dread when the first snow falls. The long gray stretch is coming, and there is nothing to do about it, or is there?\n\nYou cannot move the sun or stop a storm. But the strongest tool for enjoying winter is already with you. It is your mindset. With a few simple habits, you can learn to like the season, lift your mood, and find something to enjoy in every snowy day.\n\nIt is easy to focus on what is bad. It is more rewarding to look for what is good.\n\nDo you want to feed a small fire in your chest? Or keep that fire going through the darkest week? Maybe you only want the soft glow of home. Whatever flame you want, here is how to start it.'
      },
      {
        title: 'What did you expect?',
        text: 'There are many reasons people dread winter. Some dislike the cold. Some hate the heavy clothes. Some miss summer. All of these gripes share one root. The rhythm of life shifts, and the shift can feel scary. Is the season really harmful, or is it our bias talking?\n\nAnimals that hibernate often live longer than those that cannot. Plants grow better in soil that frost has cleaned of pests. So the urge to rest in winter is built into us. There is no reason to fight it. Lean into the rest.\n\nThe situation may set the stage, but our expectations shape how we read it.\n\nHow does that work in practice? You can start before the first snow. A few ideas can help.\n\nSet positive expectations. Winter has rough edges, but it also has bright parts. Try to name five things you like about the season, and look for them in your day. It is a small habit with a big effect.\n\nPlan a small party for the time change. Many people feel off when the clocks jump forward or back. Mark the day with something pleasant. Watch a film. Play a board game. Share a meal with people you like.\n\nPrepare your nest. When the sky is gray, a warm room feels extra good. Pick one small way to lift your space. Buy a favorite drink, hang something you like on the wall, or set a fire in the fireplace. That way, you know comfort is waiting.\n\nDone with prep? Great. The next part covers what to do once the cold has truly arrived.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Looking for the good, not the bad',
        text: 'Winter sneaks up on you, and then it is suddenly everywhere. Even good prep can fail when your socks are wet, your nose is running, and the light fades before dinner. Still, your enjoyment depends on you, not the weather. Try this simple practice. Call it active attention.\n\nCapture the moment. Take one photo a day of something small that brings you joy. It can be a warm cup, a snowflake on a scarf, or a window display. The goal is to remind yourself that the day held something good.\n\nQuestion the dark thoughts. Your mind can drift toward rough waters if you do not steer it. When a worried thought shows up, ask if it is real or just loud. At night, ask if it turned out to be true.\n\nNotice the world around you. Look at the colors and shapes. Notice what you smell, hear, and feel. When you sit in the present, worry about the future has less room.\n\nA second way to build appreciation is to use your words. Language is tied to thought. Change your words, and you can shift your mood. Try being a kind ambassador for the season. Drop one small kind remark about winter into a chat.\n\nAt first you might say how the sun makes the icicles sparkle, how the room feels snug while rain taps the window, or how nice it is to share a meal with family. The more you say these things out loud, the more of them you start to notice.\n\nFriendly talk reinforces good feelings and can wash away bad ones faster than sitting alone.\n\nA partner helps. Find someone you enjoy and trade small notes about the bright parts of the day. Two heads notice twice as much.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Comfort and good cheer',
        text: 'You come inside after a walk in the cold and text a friend about the beauty you saw. You have spent the day noticing small good things. You slip into the warm socks you saved since autumn. Still, the dark months press down on you. How do you lift your mood?\n\nMake it special. Small details can change the whole mood, and they often carry culture with them. For example, East and West both value positivity but express it differently.\n\nIn the West, people often enjoy high-energy joys like holidays, travel, or a swim in the sea. In the East, people often enjoy quieter comforts that bring a steady sense of warmth. Both kinds of joy can soften seasonal blues and act as an anchor when the blizzard howls.\n\nEvery feeling has a purpose. They are part of what makes a full life.\n\nPick one or two things that bring you peace, and do them each day. That is your first step back to your spark.\n\nOther cultures can give you hints. Almost every country has a word or ritual for winter coziness. The Danish word hygge, the Scottish ceilidh, and the German gemutlichkeit all point to the same feeling of fullness. What gives you that feeling? A favorite dish from childhood, coffee at a familiar cafe, or a weekly dinner with people you love. Winter is the perfect time to slow down and enjoy these moments on the world’s slower schedule.\n\nWant to set a warm mood when friends come over? Turn off the bright lights. Small lamps, candles, and string lights look softer and work with the dark rather than fighting it. A soft warm bulb can calm and restore you more than a cold office ceiling light.'
      },
      {
        title: 'A friend to the four elements',
        text: 'Winter is a season of balance because all four elements are present at once. Water falls as rain or snow. Earth wears down under the streams. Wind pushes clouds across the sky. Fire glows in the hearth. These forces complement each other, and you can lean into all of them.\n\nStart with earth. No matter how harsh the weather, life goes on under the snow. Feel the ground under your feet. Take a short walk, even on a cold day. The movement wakes up your muscles and clears your head. Fresh air fills your blood with oxygen. A short time outside also gives you a little sun, which winter often steals from you.\n\nBack inside, lean into fire. The shift from cold to warm can make rest feel deeper. The crackle of flames is also soothing. If you cannot settle after a hard day, sit by a fire or light a candle. A scented candle is even better.\n\nWater has long been part of winter routines. In some places, people swim in icy water and come out healthier. You can start more gently.\n\nA long trip starts with one small step.\n\nTry a sauna or a hot bath. These are common in places with long winters, like Hokkaido in Japan, Kiruna in Sweden, and Karasjok in Norway. They warm you up and feel good. A warm soak before bed helps you sleep. A quick cold rinse in the morning wakes you up.\n\nIn Finland, there is about one sauna for every two people, by most counts.'
      },
      {
        title: 'You will not melt',
        text: 'Your fire is lit, and your home is warm. But soon you have to head out for work or errands. That trip does not have to feel rough. The bad mood many people bring to winter weather is built on a few myths.\n\nMyth one, you cannot go out in bad weather. Winter can be sunny, and even rain or snow does not cancel the joy of being outside if you dress for it. A Norwegian saying goes, there is no such thing as bad weather, only bad clothes. Pick the right coat and walk.\n\nMyth two, going outside in winter is unpleasant. Give your favorite things a try in any season. You will not surf in a cold ocean without wetsuit prep, but a forest walk on a sunny January day can match the joy of a June stroll. You will not know until you try, so do not let old ideas block new fun.\n\nMyth three, winter air is bad for you. Your immune system grows stronger when it meets small challenges in gentle doses. Regular walks can help you fight off winter bugs instead of making you sick.\n\nIf you treat the cold as an opportunity, you get more out of life.\n\nNew habits are hard, so aim for short rewards. Picture how fresh you will feel outside and how good you will look walking past that office window.\n\nIf that is not enough, be kind to yourself. That does not mean staying indoors all day. It means noticing the small win of doing something good for you. Boots on. Let us go.'
      },
      {
        title: 'A few final thoughts',
        text: 'Winter is a beautiful season, yet many people find it hard. The pace of life changes, but there are good sides to that change. Set your expectations, look for small joys, make your home cozy, and enjoy what the season offers outdoors. With a little practice, winter can become your favorite time of year.\n\nTry this. Take a cue from the holidays. Think about what you love about them and give yourself that treat in winter. Rituals are powerful mood boosters.\n\nLight it up. Try softer light in your home. A candle or a small lamp instead of the big ceiling light can turn a tired room into a calm one.\n\nTake an awe walk. Go out and look for one small thing that moves you. Even if you think there is nothing to see, the world still holds quiet gifts.'
      }
    ]
  },

  'how-to.json': {
    base: { id: 'how-to', title: 'How To', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781660876817 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'Learning never really ends',
        text: 'A strange idea can turn out to be a great one. With math, prior knowledge, and a few tries, you can make a smart guess about what will happen if you test it.\n\nNASA wanted to land the Curiosity rover on Mars without crashing it or kicking up dust that would block the view, since a clear view was key. A once-ridiculous idea, the sky crane, was the answer. The crane hovered high above the surface, fired by rockets, and lowered the rover on a long tether. Because the rockets stayed high, they did not throw dust onto the landing zone. A parachute would not have worked because the rover was too heavy.\n\nIn life, we learn from other people or through trial and error.\n\nThis summary covers uncommon ways to do everyday things, like jumping, throwing a party, digging a hole, listening to music, crossing a river, throwing objects, playing football, predicting the weather, skiing, making power, taking a selfie, winning an election, and charging a phone. You probably know how to do most of these. The ideas here may help you do them in new ways. And if you do not know how, you are one of about ten thousand Americans learning something new today.'
      },
      {
        title: 'You can learn to jump much higher than you think',
        text: 'A well-trained athlete can usually jump a little over two feet without help. With a pole vault, using a springy pole and a running start, the bar can reach about twenty feet.\n\nTo jump higher, you can lean on the air itself.\n\nRunners move faster with a tailwind pushing them from behind. If you time your leap with an updraft, that rising air can lift you a little more. To catch an updraft, the wind has to be faster than your falling speed.\n\nIn free fall, most people hit a speed of about 130 miles per hour. With a sleek suit, you can slow that to about 30 miles per hour. That is still too fast to ride the wind up, unless you use a parachute or a paraglider.\n\nA suit shaped like a sailplane, used with mountain wave winds, can help you jump higher.\n\nMountain air usually climbs a short way into the sky. In some places and weather, the wave can reach the stratosphere. With a glider suit, a leap from a peak, and the right ridge lift, you might ride the wind up into the stratosphere and outclimb any plane. You would hold the world record for the highest jump. Best to leave this to the pros.'
      },
      {
        title: 'A pool party needs actual water',
        text: 'A pool can be in the ground or above it. An in-ground pool needs a hole about twenty feet by thirty feet by five feet deep, lined with plastic or rubber. If you do not have time for that, an above-ground pool is easier. The main concern is hoop stress. Hoop stress is the sideways push on the pool walls from the weight of the water and the ground below it.\n\nIf the wall is weaker than the hoop stress, the pool will burst.\n\nTo find the hoop stress, multiply water depth by water density by gravity. Then multiply that by the ratio of pool radius to wall thickness. You can rearrange the math to find any missing number. For example, wood is weaker than aluminum in raw strength, but a thick wood wall can hold more water than a thin aluminum one.\n\nA good choice for an above-ground pool is fiberglass. Its strength is about 150 megapascals.\n\nWith that kind of strength, a wall only millimeters thick can hold the water pressure.\n\nA pool party needs a pool full of water, and you have a few ways to fill it. A medium pool needs about twenty thousand gallons. Where will the water come from? You could buy bottled water online. A same-day shipment of twenty-four packs of premium water would cost around a quarter million dollars. With 150,000 bottles and only 86,400 seconds in a day, you would still run out of time, even if you opened one per second. A better plan is to use a 15,000-watt industrial shredder. You could fill the pool in just over two hours.\n\nDuring the Cold War in 1955, the US Federal Civil Defense Administration set off small nuclear tests on beer, soda, and carbonated water.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Picking a smart way to dig',
        text: 'When you think of digging, the first tool is usually a shovel. The size of the hole may force you to rethink that. A shovel moves about a third to one full cubic meter of dirt per hour. A laborer in the US earns about eighteen dollars an hour. If you are digging for buried treasure, make sure the find is worth more than the work and that the map is real.\n\nThere is only one well-recorded pirate treasure in history, but the idea of buried gold became popular after Robert Louis Stevenson wrote Treasure Island. Archaeologists and builders dig too, but treasure hunters are the most common diggers, even if the loot is rare.\n\nThe most valuable single piece of traditional treasure in the world is a 12-gram pink diamond called the Pink Star, sold in 2017 for about 71 million dollars.\n\nLet us say you find something worth digging for. Now you need a plan.\n\nFor wide and deep holes, a good method is to combine a strong vacuum with a jet of high-pressure air or water.\n\nA vacuum setup can dig about ten times faster. It also avoids damage to pipes, roots, and any buried treasure.\n\nWe should also think about the harm a hole can do. In 1590, a Spanish priest named Jose de Acosta warned that connecting the oceans across land could bring not just environmental harm but also spiritual harm, three centuries before the Panama Canal was built.\n\nIn 1699, the Scottish pirate William Kidd buried gold and silver on Gardiners Island just before his arrest. The owner of the island, John Gardiner, gave it to the crown once Kidd was caught and executed.'
      },
      {
        title: 'There are sounds a piano cannot reach',
        text: 'A standard piano has 88 keys. Its notes run from about 27 hertz to 4,186 hertz. A healthy human ear hears from 20 hertz to 20,000 hertz. To cover the full range of human hearing, a piano would need 120 keys. What if we also want notes above and below our hearing?\n\nSounds above 20,000 hertz are called ultrasound. Sounds below 20 hertz are called infrasound. Both are silent to us.\n\nEver wonder how a dog whistle works? You cannot hear it, but your dog can. It plays a note too high for human ears. Dogs can hear up to 40 kilohertz. Dogs, cats, bats, and elephants can hear well above or below our range.\n\nHigher sounds do not travel as far in the air.\n\nUltrasound travels better in water and solids, which is how electric toothbrushes, medical scans, and the echolocation of whales and dolphins work.\n\nAround 150 kilohertz is a useful limit for ultrasound in air because the sound can travel a few dozen meters. Bats can hear that pitch. A piano for bat music would need 155 keys.\n\nElephants can hear sounds as low as 15 hertz. To play music for them, you would need five extra keys on the far left.\n\nUltrasound fades faster than normal sound, but infrasound carries farther.\n\nNuclear blasts, big ocean waves, and huge machines all make infrasound. You need a tool like a spectrogram to pick it up. Ocean waves make a sound near 0.2 hertz, called microbaroms. To play it, a piano would need 235 keys.\n\nA piano that size is hard to build. A rotary woofer for infrasound and a piezo transducer for ultrasound can do the job instead.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Throwing is more of a skill than people think',
        text: 'There is a famous story about George Washington throwing a silver dollar across a river. We do not really know the physics of throwing. We do know the object flies through the air.\n\nThrowing means using a small space to launch an object with the muscles of the body. A 60-kilogram athlete can put out up to 1,200 watts of power in a throw.\n\nYou can guess how far a throw will go if you know the shape, weight, and drag of the object.\n\nThere is a calculator at xkcd.com/throw that will show you your range for different objects.\n\nA spinning object has less drag than a tumbling one. For Washington’s silver dollar, a spin would have carried it about 467 feet. A tumble would cut that to around 167 feet because of the extra drag. No one knows the truth, since the story grew up after he died.\n\nDo you need to throw things? Basic physics can help you guess your range.\n\nIn 1936, first baseman Lou Gehrig threw a silver dollar across about 400 feet of the Hudson River. The pitcher Walter Johnson threw one across the 386-foot-wide Rappahannock. They must have used a spin.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Football tricks for scoring a goal',
        text: 'Many sports are called football. Indoor soccer, foosball, American football, arena football, Paralympic football, rugby, association football, and Gaelic football are some of them. They share a ball, players on a field, and the goal of putting that ball into the other team’s net. The size and shape of the ball depend on the game.\n\nIn some games, only certain body parts can touch the ball. In American football, the quarterback handles the ball more than anyone else. Some games let you kick or throw from far out, but in American football, the quarterback cannot throw the ball straight through the goal. In association football, the goalie can throw the ball into the other team’s net. To pull that off, the goalie needs a great throwing arm to beat the other keeper.\n\nMore weight, more speed, and more power can help you charge toward the goal.\n\nOne way to get an edge is to ride a very large horse and claim there is no rule against it. To see if your horse can push through the other team, you can use the drag equation from physics.\n\nDrag equals half the drag coefficient times air density times the cross-section area times the square of speed.\n\nFaster motion meets more drag. If you double the speed, the drag force goes up four times. To beat that drag, you need more power. Power equals drag times speed.\n\nA horse can put out ten to twenty horsepower in a short burst, and one horsepower is about 746 watts.'
      },
      {
        title: 'A few final thoughts',
        text: 'You have just seen some wild ways to do ordinary things. Each one is grounded in real science. The goal has been to stretch your thinking by showing strange but accurate ways to score a goal, throw objects, build a piano that can play sounds we cannot hear, dig a hole, set up a pool, and jump much higher than is humanly normal.\n\nThis summary has been a mix of math, science, and history. You have seen great feats pulled off by athletes, politicians, and odd thinkers. The big lesson is that we all need to think in fresh ways, because that is how the best ideas appear. The plane, the smartphone, space travel, the internet, and the computer all started as strange ideas that changed the world.\n\nMost of these ideas are bad in practice, so please do not try them. But they open our minds to the fact that there is almost always more than one way to do something. That kind of thinking leads to new ideas and useful discoveries. The world can never get enough of this kind of thinking. It drives human progress.\n\nTry this. You can dig a hole without shoveling. Use a vacuum cleaner and a jet of air or water. See how deep you can go with those tools. It is a bad idea, but you never know what you might find.'
      }
    ]
  },

  'how-we-got-to-now.json': {
    base: { id: 'how-we-got-to-now', title: 'How We Got to Now', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781661276129 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'Small things often lead to the biggest inventions',
        text: 'New ideas show up every day. We do not hear about most of them, because they do not change our lives, at least not yet. But many of the most useful inventions in history started out small and quiet. They have become such a part of daily life that we barely notice them.\n\nSteven Johnson has long been curious about science and technology. He looked into the hidden story behind some of the most powerful inventions of our time, from mirrors and telescopes to telephones, air conditioning, and lights.\n\nWe all use these things every day. We do not think much about them, but we need them. Johnson also found that many of these inventions grew out of completely different problems. Mirrors grew out of glass jewelry. Telephones grew out of echoes in caves. Each one has shaped how humans live.\n\nMany of the world’s best ideas came from regular people, not lone geniuses. That is good news for the rest of us.\n\nSolving one problem often solves others along the way. Most of the tools we use today were not designed as full solutions. They grew over time, and they turned into the all-purpose tools we now rely on. A small action tends to lead to another. That chain reaction creates new ways of living and, in nature, new ways to survive.\n\nInventions are rarely born from a single flash of insight. They come from long work, steady patience, and many bumps along the way.\n\nIn this summary, you will learn about some of the most life-changing inventions and where they came from. The story may surprise you. It might even push you to be more grateful for the tools in your life, or to start thinking about your own idea. You never know. The next big thing might come from you.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Glass and mirrors started as a single grain of sand',
        text: 'Have you ever wondered where the glass in your mirror came from? Or the glass in your window? To find the answer, we have to travel to the edge of the Sahara Desert, to Libya, and back in time about 26 million years.\n\nGlass is just glass, right? Not quite. Glass gave us a window to see through, jewelry to wear, mirrors to study our faces, and telescopes to study the stars. It lets us see ourselves and the universe. Glass even brings small works of art into our homes. It is far more useful than most of us realize.\n\nBack to that desert.\n\nA spike in temperature, still unexplained, changed the chemical makeup of the sand. The grains fused into a solid. This happened across a whole stretch of the desert, not just one spot. Many years later, an explorer found this hard layer of glass and brought a piece home.\n\nThe smallest grain of sand in a faraway desert led to some of the world’s biggest inventions. You are never too small to make a mark.\n\nThat single piece of glass soon became very valuable. It was used in jewelry for an Egyptian ruler.\n\nRoman emperors also loved glass jewelry. That demand helped create the glass trade in Venice, which grew into the famous Murano industry. At that time, glass jewelry was very profitable. But the story did not end there.\n\nMore work with glass led to mirrors. Now we can see ourselves. Glass was also shaped into microscopes and telescopes.\n\nFrom one grain of sand in a Libyan desert, we have mirrors, jewelry, microscopes, telescopes, and windows.'
      },
      {
        title: 'A simple block of ice led to modern refrigeration',
        text: 'When you drop an ice cube into a drink on a hot day, do you think about how ice first came to be seen as a way to cool things? It is just frozen water, after all.\n\nFor the air conditioning in your home, the frozen food in your freezer, and the ability to freeze eggs for later, you can thank Frederic Tudor. This Boston businessman was the first to see that ice could be a serious business, and it made him very rich.\n\nOn a trip to the Caribbean with his brother when he was only 17, Tudor saw that people in hot countries would pay well for ice. He had grown up in New England and had never thought of this. After seeing the heat and the struggles of life in the Caribbean, he decided to ship ice south and make a fortune.\n\nThe big money flowing from the tropics to the ice barons of New England sent a signal around the world. There was money in cold. That set inventors off in search of the next step, artificial cooling.\n\nThose curious minds took the simple idea of an ice cube in a drink and ran with it. Now cold is used in countless ways, from saving old artifacts to freezing food for storage to fertility care. Of course, we also use it to keep our homes cool in the worst of summer.\n\nFreezing temperatures have opened up new medical treatments. Organ donations and fertility care are possible because of cold technology.\n\nAll of this started with one young man who wanted to feel cooler on a trip to the Caribbean. He just used his business sense and may have changed the world.\n\nWillis Haviland Carrier built the world’s first air conditioning unit in 1902.'
      },
      {
        title: 'The telephone can be traced back to the earliest humans',
        text: 'Most of us keep a phone within arm’s reach all day. Many people even sleep with theirs under the pillow. But have you thought about how that little device came to be? It may surprise you to learn that the story goes all the way back to the earliest humans, the Neanderthals.\n\nTo see the link, we have to travel back about a million years to the area we now call Paris. At that time, retreating seas had carved out long limestone caves that stretched into Burgundy and beyond. Inside were tall stalactites, stalagmites, and many chambers. The earliest Neanderthals lived in these caves, as shown by the cave paintings that have been found.\n\nA few thousand years later, a musical researcher from Paris found that the caves were used for more than quiet meetings. They were also used for music. The cave paintings were placed in spots where the chambers would amplify and change the human voice. Neanderthals used these spaces to change the sound of their voices during rituals. This is one of the earliest examples of voice enhancement and sound shaping.\n\nFor most of history, people have tried to understand how to change and then reproduce the human voice. Many of these efforts shaped modern communication, and the telephone is one of the biggest examples.\n\nThe ability to talk with people thousands of miles away is one of the most powerful inventions of all time.\n\nIn 1876, Alexander Graham Bell patented the telephone. His experiments led to recording, changing, and sending sound, just as the Neanderthals had done. From there, the phone kept changing until it became the slim, cordless device most of us carry today. Who would have thought that a modern smartphone was born from Neanderthals singing in a cave?'
      },
      {
        title: 'You can thank old sewers for your modern subway',
        text: 'Getting to work is easier because of a vast network of underground tunnels. These let us zip to the office and back in far less time than it would take above ground. Underground travel has reshaped how cities move. Where did it start?\n\nThe truth is that it started with a need for better sewers in Chicago.\n\nIn the 1800s, Chicago was battling widespread disease with a clear link to poor hygiene. The city was flat and low. The soil made it nearly impossible to dig traditional underground sewers, like the ones in European cities. An engineer named Ellis Chesbrough was asked to find a solution. The problem was made worse by outbreaks of cholera and dysentery. City leaders hoped a cleaner city would help. We now know that waste is closely linked to disease.\n\nChesbrough had a long history of working on railways and canals. He had an idea. They could not dig down, so they would lift the city up and then build the sewers below. That plan led to Chicago’s model sewage system, which was soon copied by cities across America.\n\nThe new sewers cleaned up Chicago’s waste, and the same idea also brought fresh, clean water to homes.\n\nBut one idea often leads to another. A network of tunnels under a city could be used for more than water. By 1863, London had its first underground train, a steam line running beneath the city. The New York Subway came next, followed by metro systems in cities around the world.\n\nWe picture cities by their skylines, that tall reach toward the sky. But those city towers would not stand without the hidden world below.'
      },
      {
        title: 'From whales to lightbulbs, artificial light has changed everything',
        text: 'Can you picture a world with no light after sunset? In winter, you would get only a few hours of dull daylight before the dark took over. Most of us have electric light to thank that this is not our life. Yet in many countries, light is rationed or even cut off without warning.\n\nIf you had been in space about 150 years ago, you would not have seen much light from Earth. About 100 years ago, that changed. Today, the lit areas of our planet give off about 6,000 times more light than they did back then. All of that is thanks to a switch on the wall.\n\nThe simple lightbulb gave us light, reset our body clocks, opened new ways to communicate, and may even lead to new energy sources in the future.\n\nThe first light came thousands of years ago from the ability to make and keep fire. The Romans made oil lamps, but those still used fire, which dimmed and went out. After that, candles were the most common light. For many, this meant tallow candles made from animal fat, which gave off thick, black smoke that hurt the lungs.\n\nThere was hope on the horizon, though, thanks to a storm that blew an American sailor off course. He met a sperm whale in the middle of the Atlantic. He somehow managed to kill it and bring it back to shore. When they cut it open, they found that spermaceti could be made into candles with a much brighter flame. Sadly, this also fueled a brutal whaling industry.\n\nThat practice was finally stopped when Thomas Edison invented the lightbulb while working on electric lamps. In a short time, homes went from dim flames to bright light, and the long dark nights lost their grip.\n\nEdison was a young wizard at Menlo Park. He had a flash of an idea, and within a few years, his invention was lighting up the world.'
      },
      {
        title: 'A few final thoughts',
        text: 'Some of the most basic things in our daily lives have stories that go back centuries, even millions of years. Who would have linked our phone calls to cave paintings and tunnels under the earth? Or the New York Subway to a sewer in Chicago?\n\nSmall ideas can grow into major changes. But they also create new problems. We have lightbulbs, but they need power. That means we need electricity, which can harm the environment when it is made the wrong way. So while inventions are impressive, we have to keep finding better ways to use and improve them.\n\nIt is also true that not everyone has clean running water. Not everyone has an air conditioner for the hottest days. Not everyone has a phone. We should be grateful for the inventions that have reached us over the last few centuries. Our lives would be far worse without them.\n\nEvolution never really stops. One small idea leads to another, which leads to another, and ties into something new. Maybe you have a life-changing idea inside you, and you just have not developed it yet. Once you do, you may end up with something that looks very different from your first thought, but it works, and it could make the world a little better.\n\nThat is a thought worth holding.\n\nTry this. Each evening, thank something simple in your life. Do not take the basics for granted when many people still do not have them.\n\nIf an idea keeps coming back to you, give it a little more attention.\n\nWork with others when you want to grow an idea. New voices can take your first thought further than you could on your own.'
      }
    ]
  },

  'humankind.json': {
    base: { id: 'humankind', title: 'Humankind', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781661407711 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'The better side of people is often overlooked',
        text: 'Human beings have a rough reputation. We are known for jealousy, pride, anger, and spite, and only rarely for kindness and care. And yet, history is full of moments when human kindness made the real difference.\n\nRutger Bregman makes a bold case that people are not so bad after all. He suggests that we have survived one catastrophe after another because we care for each other, show empathy, and form strong bonds. Many people brush this idea aside. Bregman argues that, if we take it seriously, we could build a better society for everyone.\n\nHumans have made it through the worst events in history. Scholars still debate whether that is luck or our ability to care.\n\nDuring major disasters, it is easy to assume that people panic and look out for themselves. That is often not what happens. Bregman points to the attacks of September 11 in New York. People were terrified, but they were not shoving each other out of the way. They were helping each other, holding doors, and giving up their place to the slower and more vulnerable.\n\nIt is normal to feel a flash of panic. But again and again, people have shown the ability to step past that first fear and act with their better side. It is easy to assume that human nature is just greed and self-interest. Looking at the good side of the scale is always a better choice. When you do, it helps you act with more empathy and understanding.\n\nWhen the pressure rises, we often think of others before ourselves, even if the popular story says otherwise.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Disasters bring out the best in communities near and far',
        text: 'Again and again, we have seen that disasters, both natural and human-made, bring out the best in people. After Hurricane Katrina hit New Orleans, the news was full of stories about crime and looting. There were reports of murders, rapes, and other dark acts. It led many to believe that, when things go wrong, people only look out for themselves and toss everyone else aside.\n\nOnce the dust settled, the truth came out. People had traveled miles to help strangers, desperate to do their part and save lives.\n\nThe common view is that, in hard times, it is everyone for themselves. The truth is that we come together and do what we can.\n\nLook at most disasters in history and you will see the same pattern. People gather. They help. It is often assumed that hard times bring out the worst in us, but studies have failed to back that up with hard evidence.\n\nResearch shows that disasters bring out the best in people, and very few findings in sociology are backed by as much evidence yet ignored as much as this one.\n\nIgnoring the evidence and assuming that people will turn on each other can be harmful. We end up suspicious of others and unsure of their offers to help. If we open our eyes to the truth, life can be much better for everyone.\n\nRather than doubting those who want to help, allow yourself to believe that they care.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Are humans smarter, or just friendlier?',
        text: 'Human beings are not that smart when you compare us to other species. The human brain is a complex and impressive organ, but we are slow, we overthink, and we are not very strong. So how have we lasted so long?\n\nMany species that lived on the planet before us are now gone, and yet we are still here, walking around as if we own the place. Some say it is because we are superior, but the evidence keeps saying otherwise. Many animals can kill us without a second thought.\n\nHumans like to think they are the strongest and the smartest, but that is not true. There has to be another reason we have survived for so long.\n\nA strong view is that it is not our power, intelligence, or strength that has kept us going. It is our friendliness. We look out for each other, and that gives us strength in numbers.\n\nHumans are not the only species that shows empathy. Animals show it too. A dog comforts a grieving owner, or an animal steps in to save a person in danger.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Oxytocin works for you and against you',
        text: 'Most people have heard of oxytocin, a chemical released by the brain at certain moments, like during childbirth or when you are close to someone you love. It makes you feel held and warm, and it pulls you toward the people you care about. It is a bonding chemical that helps us feel safe.\n\nBut oxytocin has a flip side. Studies from the University of Amsterdam show that the warm effects only happen when you are with people close to you. With a partner, family, or friends, oxytocin feels like a hug. With people outside that circle, it can do the opposite.\n\nOxytocin is a bonding chemical, but it can also push you away from strangers and people you do not like.\n\nThat may be one reason humans can be cold or harsh toward people they do not know.\n\nOxytocin does not fuel universal love. It powers feelings of my people first, and that is a basic part of how it works.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Deep down, we are afraid of aggression',
        text: 'With all this talk of people being kind and ready to help, you might wonder why soldiers go to war and shoot to kill. In war, soldiers are trained to fight, and on the battlefield, they are expected to do whatever it takes to protect their country or their cause. How does that fit with the idea that humans are kind and helpful?\n\nThe question of human nature gets tangled up by the fact that humans fight wars. But even in the toughest battles, many soldiers avoid direct conflict.\n\nBregman writes about a colonel who served in the war in 1942 and later became a historian. He spent his life asking the very question we are asking now.\n\nHe interviewed many veterans and found that most of them never fired their weapon. Many actively avoided it. This was not because they were scared or did not know what they were doing. Some of these soldiers had been in the field for years. In his later book, the historian said it was a basic human instinct that stopped them from killing another person at close range, a deep fear of facing aggression head on.\n\nHumans are wired to avoid aggression from others. Understanding and empathy feel safer.\n\nEmpathy and kindness show up in the strangest moments. For the soldiers who did not fire, it seemed to be human nature itself that held them back.'
      },
      {
        title: 'If humans are kind, where does cruelty come from?',
        text: 'History is full of shocking examples of human cruelty. Even with the evidence Bregman offers, there is a lot that works against his view. But on closer look, researchers have pulled apart some of the worst acts in history and explained why people followed the orders of twisted leaders. Not every person on the planet is good, and there will always be a few who go against the grain.\n\nTake Adolf Hitler, for example, or Pol Pot. Why did these notoriously cruel men have so many followers hanging on their words? Social psychology has an answer.\n\nStudies show that even though humans are kind at their core, they are also capable of terrible acts against other humans. It only takes a small change in the situation to shift how a person thinks and acts. We follow the orders of a person in power because we assume that is what we should do. That helps explain why followers listened to Hitler’s twisted speeches and carried out his orders.\n\nA person’s situation has a huge effect on what they think and do. A bad setting can push someone to act in a way that does not match their normal character.\n\nBregman describes the famous Stanford Prison Experiment from 1971. Nine men were put in a fake jail and told to act as prisoners. Another nine were told to act as guards. Things went dark fast. The guards fell into the role of power, partly because of the uniform. The prisoners were pushed close to the edge of what they could handle. In the end, many of the prisoners showed signs of depression and anxiety.\n\nEven in this extreme case, the study shows how a change in the situation can change how a person thinks, feels, and acts.\n\nOur behavior is often shaped by the situation we are in.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Human bonds can pull you off the right path',
        text: 'If Hitler’s followers were shaped by a bad situation, how do you explain why they kept following him and fighting in the Nazi army, even when it was clear that the war was lost?\n\nDuring the Second World War, the soldiers fighting against the Nazis often talked about how hard it was to break the strength of the Nazi army, not because of force, but because of spirit.\n\nNazi soldiers in World War Two were known for their strong bonds. That made them tough to beat, because they would fight for each other to the end.\n\nAs soldiers were captured and questioned, the same answer kept coming up. Most of them did not really believe in Hitler’s ideas. But once they were in the situation, they kept going because they had formed deep friendships with the men beside them. They had become brothers, and the fear of letting those brothers down was strong enough to keep them going.\n\nThe human need to belong to a group of people who think and feel the same way is powerful. Even when the cause is clearly wrong, the bonds and friendships are strong enough to keep people on that path.\n\nWe all want to belong, and once we find a group we connect with, we will do almost anything to avoid letting them down.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Give someone power and watch them change',
        text: 'Many studies have looked at power. They show that if you give an ordinary person a lot of power, it changes them over time. A lot of research backs this up.\n\nLarge amounts of power can corrupt a person. It changes how they talk and how they act around others.\n\nPower can turn someone selfish, arrogant, and rude, and it can make them act on impulse. Power also changes how they communicate, making them more dismissive and casual. A 2014 American study showed that power even changes how the brain works, dulling a natural process called mirroring.\n\nMirroring is a natural response that we all do without noticing. If someone starts laughing hard, you will often find yourself laughing, even if you have no idea what is funny. A person with a lot of power mirrors less, and that is a problem. Mirroring is how we connect and bond with the people around us. So powerful people lose the ability to form genuine bonds, which makes it harder for them to show empathy.\n\nPower tends to corrupt, and total power corrupts completely. That is a warning worth keeping in mind.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Build a future on the best of human nature',
        text: 'With all this evidence that people are not so bad, can we use it to build a better future? Bregman thinks we can.\n\nWe have to look at how we motivate people, and we have to put trust at the center. We have grown more suspicious over the years, and that suspicion affects how we connect with each other. Used well, trust is a powerful tool because it spreads. A society built on trust is a kinder place and leans into the good side of people.\n\nA society that values trust puts more weight on kindness and support. That is a starting point for change.\n\nOn motivation, Bregman argues that, instead of forcing people to do things, we need to help them want to do them in the first place. A society that motivates itself gets better results, and the work feels more meaningful for everyone.\n\nAll of this starts with how we raise our kids. Bregman believes that, if we let children play freely instead of limiting them, they will grow up seeing the world as a more positive and creative place.\n\nLetting children be creative in their play helps them see the world as a kind and creative place. That is how we build a brighter future.'
      },
      {
        title: 'A few final thoughts',
        text: 'The media has trained us to believe that human nature is nothing but greed, selfishness, and spite. The truth is very different. Again and again, the evidence shows that, when things get rough, we stand up for each other and do what we can to help.\n\nOf course, the world is not perfect, and terrible acts have been committed over the years. But studying human nature and the reasons behind our actions can shed light on behavior under pressure. That does not let the worst leaders or criminals off the hook, but it can help explain why some people feel forced to follow them without question.\n\nBy focusing on the good side of human nature instead of the bad, we can build a society that works better for the generations to come.\n\nThe damage of assuming the worst spills into our relationships. We expect everyone to betray us, but that is often not true. There are genuinely good people out there who want to help others. These acts of kindness bring them joy. If you assume everyone will hurt you, you let suspicion run the show.\n\nThe be kind idea fits here. We need to be kind to ourselves, and we should give others the benefit of the doubt. Do not judge someone’s actions until they have shown you they cannot be trusted. Stay careful, but do not assume the worst.\n\nTry this. Think about the last time you heard about a local disaster. How did you react? Did you feel a pull to help? Write down your thoughts and actions. They are evidence that people are wired to be kind first.\n\nAre there people in your life leading you somewhere you do not want to go, but you follow them because you feel a sense of kinship? We are often drawn to situations that make us feel part of something. Not everything is worth being part of.'
      }
    ]
  }
};
